1
00:00:14,500 --> 00:00:17,875
My name is Faraj Salamah from
the town of Tabqa in Raqqa Province

2
00:00:18,791 --> 00:00:20,458
I am 27 years old

3
00:00:21,125 --> 00:00:23,125
Married and have one daughter

4
00:00:25,041 --> 00:00:26,625
At the beginning of 2016

5
00:00:28,375 --> 00:00:31,625
I was working in agriculture in rural Tabqa

6
00:00:33,625 --> 00:00:37,291
Things were relatively stable in the area

7
00:00:38,500 --> 00:00:43,500
On February 19 2016, a Friday

8
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:46,750
The situation was normal

9
00:00:48,833 --> 00:00:50,625
I was getting ready for Friday prayer

10
00:00:52,041 --> 00:00:54,666
When I was about to leave the bathroom

11
00:00:55,208 --> 00:00:57,791
Preparing to go to the mosque

12
00:00:58,583 --> 00:01:00,000
I heard movement outside the bathroom

13
00:01:00,208 --> 00:01:02,000
Then someone knocked on the door

14
00:01:02,750 --> 00:01:04,125
He told me not to come out

15
00:01:05,750 --> 00:01:08,291
I waited for about half an hour

16
00:01:09,583 --> 00:01:13,416
I noticed armed men

17
00:01:13,875 --> 00:01:16,208
From ISIS inside the house

18
00:01:16,500 --> 00:01:18,583
I heard weapons and wireless devices

19
00:01:19,291 --> 00:01:20,458
It became clear it was a raid

20
00:01:21,416 --> 00:01:23,166
Things were not normal

21
00:01:24,541 --> 00:01:29,416
After half an hour someone ordered me to leave the bathroom

22
00:01:30,041 --> 00:01:32,916
Everyone outside was armed

23
00:01:34,750 --> 00:01:37,000
They ordered me to stand in front of the house

24
00:01:37,541 --> 00:01:40,333
And I found my brothers outside too

25
00:01:41,041 --> 00:01:43,500
Sitting on chairs while ISIS members searched the house

26
00:01:45,125 --> 00:01:48,041
I realized the village was surrounded and being searched

27
00:01:48,458 --> 00:01:50,083
Every now and then an ISIS vehicle arrived

28
00:01:50,583 --> 00:01:52,625
Bringing two or three of my cousins

29
00:01:53,083 --> 00:01:53,958
Then leaving again

30
00:01:54,875 --> 00:01:56,625
We stayed until the afternoon prayer

31
00:01:57,500 --> 00:02:00,083
For nearly three hours or more

32
00:02:03,166 --> 00:02:05,750
Then ISIS members put us in vehicles

33
00:02:06,458 --> 00:02:10,125
The first building we entered was the Islamic Police base

34
00:02:11,583 --> 00:02:16,458
Inside I saw relatives from a nearby village

35
00:02:17,041 --> 00:02:19,958
Some of my brothers had gone to Friday prayers before us

36
00:02:20,791 --> 00:02:21,750
So they followed them to the mosque

37
00:02:22,500 --> 00:02:25,250
And while they were praying, they were all arrested

38
00:02:27,166 --> 00:02:28,916
They put us all together

39
00:02:29,375 --> 00:02:32,458
Every 10 minutes cars arrived

40
00:02:32,750 --> 00:02:36,583
Taking several people away to unknown destinations

41
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:39,208
The cars kept coming

42
00:02:39,708 --> 00:02:42,250
We were about 30 people or more

43
00:02:43,041 --> 00:02:44,416
All brothers and cousins

44
00:02:46,250 --> 00:02:47,958
Finally, it was our turn

45
00:02:48,083 --> 00:02:51,416
We got in blindfolded, not knowing where we were going

46
00:02:53,541 --> 00:02:55,125
We drove a short distance

47
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,416
I believe still within Tabqa

48
00:02:59,541 --> 00:03:03,583
When we entered, we realized it was the Bourj (Tower) Prison of ISIS

49
00:03:05,291 --> 00:03:08,583
We got out of the vehicle and lined up facing the wall

50
00:03:08,791 --> 00:03:10,958
Beside other blindfolded prisoners I could sense nearby

51
00:03:11,125 --> 00:03:12,958
It was completely silent

52
00:03:14,708 --> 00:03:17,208
They began opening doors and distributing the prisoners

53
00:03:18,666 --> 00:03:21,666
They placed two or three in each
solitary cell because of the overcrowding

54
00:03:21,958 --> 00:03:23,291
I was put in a solitary cell too

55
00:03:24,583 --> 00:03:26,291
With two of my cousins

56
00:03:28,041 --> 00:03:32,625
Next to us were other solitary cells, and opposite were group cells

57
00:03:35,375 --> 00:03:37,000
They started taking prisoners for interrogation

58
00:03:37,166 --> 00:03:40,250
To collect personal information about us

59
00:03:40,916 --> 00:03:41,875
Then returning us

60
00:03:42,333 --> 00:03:44,583
During the first day, no one was taken for interrogation

61
00:03:46,833 --> 00:03:49,333
After 2:30 a.m.

62
00:03:50,250 --> 00:03:55,666
We heard noise as they brought in a large number of prisoners

63
00:03:57,458 --> 00:04:00,208
We could see through the cell door

64
00:04:01,083 --> 00:04:06,250
Watching through the small window, we saw the corridor

65
00:04:07,333 --> 00:04:10,166
We saw they had arrested many young men

66
00:04:11,041 --> 00:04:14,166
Blindfolded in the same way as us

67
00:04:14,375 --> 00:04:16,875
Lined up against the wall in the corridor

68
00:04:17,666 --> 00:04:18,916
Then they started distributing them

69
00:04:19,583 --> 00:04:20,791
They put them with us

70
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,291
It turned out they were our relatives from Jarnieh, rural Tabqa

71
00:04:25,583 --> 00:04:26,416
We recognized each other

72
00:04:26,458 --> 00:04:28,416
It was the first time I had seen them

73
00:04:30,500 --> 00:04:31,583
After two days

74
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:34,583
They transferred me to another cell

75
00:04:35,208 --> 00:04:36,625
It was not solitary

76
00:04:36,750 --> 00:04:40,791
There were around 10 or 11 people

77
00:04:41,333 --> 00:04:42,333
All of them my relatives

78
00:04:44,083 --> 00:04:46,250
We started asking each other about our family members

79
00:04:46,500 --> 00:04:49,166
I asked about my brothers and father
because I didn’t know where they were

80
00:04:49,333 --> 00:04:52,791
But I could hear their voices from inside the solitary cells

81
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,125
Even though our group cell was far from theirs

82
00:04:55,833 --> 00:05:00,875
Located in a different section outside the solitary area

83
00:05:01,583 --> 00:05:03,833
To reach it, you had to pass through the kitchen

84
00:05:04,083 --> 00:05:05,541
Then another room

85
00:05:06,041 --> 00:05:08,166
Before arriving at the large group cell

86
00:05:10,291 --> 00:05:12,833
One of my relatives told me he had been with my father

87
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:14,041
And reassured me that he was fine

88
00:05:14,166 --> 00:05:17,458
But we still didn’t know why we had been arrested or for what reason

89
00:05:19,166 --> 00:05:21,833
Every week

90
00:05:22,666 --> 00:05:24,791
They would select two or three people and release them

91
00:05:25,583 --> 00:05:28,041
We were in contact with the group cell next to us

92
00:05:28,791 --> 00:05:31,583
The cell door was confusing in layout

93
00:05:31,791 --> 00:05:34,500
It didn’t open to the hallway but faced a wall

94
00:05:36,500 --> 00:05:39,875
We spoke with them through the electrical outlet

95
00:05:40,041 --> 00:05:41,958
Where one of my brothers and cousins were

96
00:05:42,416 --> 00:05:43,708
I kept in touch with them constantly

97
00:05:45,250 --> 00:05:47,916
I stayed for 27 days

98
00:05:48,750 --> 00:05:50,041
In that group cell

99
00:05:50,666 --> 00:05:53,958
Until only my two cousins and I remained

100
00:05:55,375 --> 00:05:56,625
The rest were released

101
00:05:57,833 --> 00:06:02,791
Without knowing which of my relatives and
brothers were still in the remaining group cells

102
00:06:07,083 --> 00:06:08,541
I was called in for interrogation

103
00:06:08,933 --> 00:06:10,850
To be asked about my brother Ibrahim

104
00:06:11,741 --> 00:06:13,750
Whom I thought had been detained with us

105
00:06:14,175 --> 00:06:16,050
But I hadn’t heard his voice

106
00:06:17,116 --> 00:06:18,366
So I realized they hadn’t arrested him

107
00:06:19,808 --> 00:06:22,641
I answered that I didn’t know and that he was in Tabqa

108
00:06:23,966 --> 00:06:25,566
And that we usually went together to Friday prayers

109
00:06:26,133 --> 00:06:27,416
But I didn’t see him because you arrived before the prayer

110
00:06:27,483 --> 00:06:29,608
And took us away before it started

111
00:06:31,666 --> 00:06:33,833
He took me to the disciplinary cell (solitary cell)

112
00:06:33,958 --> 00:06:36,041
And began asking what weapons I owned

113
00:06:36,166 --> 00:06:37,333
I told him I had no weapons at all

114
00:06:38,291 --> 00:06:40,708
I said the only weapon was the hunting rifle

115
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:42,666
That you found in the house

116
00:06:43,416 --> 00:06:45,833
He repeated his question, claiming we had buried weapons

117
00:06:46,416 --> 00:06:48,250
Accusing me of belonging to the Free Syrian Army

118
00:06:48,500 --> 00:06:49,708
Because my brother was with the Free Syrian Army

119
00:06:50,375 --> 00:06:52,083
I told him my brother

120
00:06:52,708 --> 00:06:56,375
Is responsible for himself, and we have nothing to do with him

121
00:06:56,625 --> 00:06:57,583
He said, No problem then

122
00:06:57,666 --> 00:06:58,791
And took me to a room

123
00:06:59,375 --> 00:07:00,375
Not a normal room

124
00:07:00,958 --> 00:07:01,708
It was smaller than a solitary cell

125
00:07:01,791 --> 00:07:04,291
They called it the disciplinary cell

126
00:07:04,875 --> 00:07:07,166
About 60 centimeters wide

127
00:07:07,875 --> 00:07:09,416
And about one and a half meters long

128
00:07:11,250 --> 00:07:12,958
I stayed there for four days

129
00:07:13,083 --> 00:07:14,875
They gave us food through the door

130
00:07:15,416 --> 00:07:18,458
And at prayer times, they allowed us out only for ablution

131
00:07:19,916 --> 00:07:21,291
After four days, he brought me back for interrogation

132
00:07:21,375 --> 00:07:23,416
And asked what new information I had this time

133
00:07:23,666 --> 00:07:24,875
I told him I knew nothing

134
00:07:25,583 --> 00:07:27,166
When I entered the disciplinary cell

135
00:07:27,291 --> 00:07:29,083
There was someone next to me

136
00:07:29,791 --> 00:07:31,750
From Safira

137
00:07:33,166 --> 00:07:35,416
He told me, When I arrived here, your father...

138
00:07:35,625 --> 00:07:38,916
Was inside this room

139
00:07:39,583 --> 00:07:41,500
They took him out and put me in his place

140
00:07:41,750 --> 00:07:43,416
Then I began to hear my father’s voice

141
00:07:43,541 --> 00:07:46,333
Because the disciplinary cells were in the same corridor

142
00:07:46,541 --> 00:07:49,166
That contained the solitary and group cells

143
00:07:50,625 --> 00:07:52,125
So I could hear my father’s voice

144
00:07:52,583 --> 00:07:54,541
And two of my brothers

145
00:07:54,791 --> 00:07:57,500
And a cousin of mine, I could hear them clearly

146
00:07:58,708 --> 00:08:01,625
That’s how I knew who remained
in prison and who had been released

147
00:08:01,833 --> 00:08:03,833
Late at night

148
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:05,625
We would talk to each other

149
00:08:05,750 --> 00:08:08,166
Without ISIS members noticing

150
00:08:09,541 --> 00:08:11,708
Or maybe they noticed and pretended not to

151
00:08:13,166 --> 00:08:13,916
After another four days

152
00:08:14,041 --> 00:08:16,000
He brought me back for interrogation again

153
00:08:16,208 --> 00:08:17,916
The interrogator asked if I had any new statements

154
00:08:18,083 --> 00:08:21,000
I told him I’d already said everything I knew

155
00:08:21,166 --> 00:08:22,416
And I had nothing new

156
00:08:23,208 --> 00:08:23,250
He put me in a solitary cell

157
00:08:25,208 --> 00:08:26,208
I entered the solitary cell

158
00:08:26,333 --> 00:08:29,041
And found a young man from Daraa

159
00:08:30,541 --> 00:08:31,166
He told me

160
00:08:31,208 --> 00:08:32,916
Your brother was with me

161
00:08:33,041 --> 00:08:34,875
Then they moved him to the group cell

162
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:37,958
After midnight

163
00:08:38,208 --> 00:08:40,416
I would talk with my father. He heard me and I heard him

164
00:08:40,708 --> 00:08:42,916
One of my brothers was with him

165
00:08:43,666 --> 00:08:46,541
And they also had no charges brought against them

166
00:08:46,791 --> 00:08:48,625
Another brother was far away in a solitary cell

167
00:08:49,458 --> 00:08:51,333
I couldn’t communicate with him well

168
00:08:51,458 --> 00:08:53,041
But we could hear each other’s voices

169
00:08:53,291 --> 00:08:54,458
And knew we were in the same prison

170
00:08:57,041 --> 00:08:59,166
My cousins were on my right and left

171
00:09:01,125 --> 00:09:02,375
On the right and on the left

172
00:09:02,625 --> 00:09:05,208
After three or four days

173
00:09:06,500 --> 00:09:08,833
They took one of my cousins out of the solitary cells

174
00:09:09,125 --> 00:09:10,125
That were beside me

175
00:09:10,250 --> 00:09:13,208
And moved him to another solitary cell

176
00:09:13,791 --> 00:09:15,833
Then they brought in two women

177
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:21,458
About 25 to 26 years old

178
00:09:22,750 --> 00:09:24,416
In the prison, we communicated

179
00:09:24,625 --> 00:09:26,666
Through the water taps

180
00:09:28,333 --> 00:09:31,708
We spoke and heard each other, though not clearly

181
00:09:33,541 --> 00:09:35,958
ISIS had arrested them

182
00:09:36,250 --> 00:09:37,916
For walking repeatedly near the base

183
00:09:38,083 --> 00:09:39,416
Accusing them of filming

184
00:09:39,583 --> 00:09:41,916
And sending footage to the Global Coalition Against ISIS

185
00:09:42,916 --> 00:09:44,708
They were taken for interrogation

186
00:09:44,916 --> 00:09:46,541
After midnight

187
00:09:46,708 --> 00:09:48,958
We could hear the voices of the women and the torture

188
00:09:50,833 --> 00:09:53,250
We endured and prayed, saying, God is sufficient
for us, and He is the best disposer of affairs

189
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:55,333
Then they would be brought back

190
00:09:55,541 --> 00:09:59,041
So exhausted they couldn’t even talk to us

191
00:09:59,583 --> 00:10:01,750
We couldn’t communicate with them properly

192
00:10:03,458 --> 00:10:04,708
After a while

193
00:10:05,208 --> 00:10:07,875
They took out my cousin who was on the left side

194
00:10:08,458 --> 00:10:09,500
And moved him to another solitary cell

195
00:10:09,583 --> 00:10:10,708
Then they brought women again

196
00:10:11,041 --> 00:10:13,375
And placed them in the solitary cell next to mine

197
00:10:13,708 --> 00:10:16,500
So I ended up between two solitary cells holding women

198
00:10:16,958 --> 00:10:18,250
With the women detained the last time

199
00:10:18,375 --> 00:10:20,125
There were young children with them

200
00:10:21,333 --> 00:10:23,750
They took a child from one of the women

201
00:10:24,666 --> 00:10:25,833
For about a week

202
00:10:25,958 --> 00:10:28,000
We couldn’t sleep or eat

203
00:10:28,291 --> 00:10:32,000
Because of the woman’s cries over her baby’s separation

204
00:10:32,458 --> 00:10:33,750
Who I think was an infant

205
00:10:33,875 --> 00:10:34,875
Less than one year old

206
00:10:40,083 --> 00:10:42,583
I used to see, in the solitary cell or the group cell

207
00:10:42,791 --> 00:10:49,750
The names of prisoners, their arrest dates, and reasons

208
00:10:50,916 --> 00:10:55,250
I found the name of a young man I knew from the town of Tabqa

209
00:10:55,541 --> 00:11:00,416
He had written his name and his case on the wall

210
00:11:02,583 --> 00:11:04,791
His name was Muhannad Raja al-Harmoush

211
00:11:05,708 --> 00:11:08,791
They placed him in front of the solitary cell door

212
00:11:09,958 --> 00:11:11,916
Around one o’clock after midnight

213
00:11:13,833 --> 00:11:16,500
I saw them through the window asking his name

214
00:11:16,875 --> 00:11:19,791
He answered, Muhannad Raja al-Harmoush,
so I recognized him immediately

215
00:11:20,041 --> 00:11:23,083
They asked him, What’s your case about?

216
00:11:23,916 --> 00:11:26,041
He said, Mocking ISIS

217
00:11:26,291 --> 00:11:27,750
The interrogator asked, Why do you mock?

218
00:11:27,916 --> 00:11:30,166
He replied, explaining that what he
said was only a joke, nothing more

219
00:11:30,791 --> 00:11:31,916
The interrogator said, No problem with that

220
00:11:32,833 --> 00:11:34,958
Muhannad stayed standing for five minutes

221
00:11:35,208 --> 00:11:36,875
They shackled his hands and blindfolded him

222
00:11:36,958 --> 00:11:38,291
Then took him elsewhere

223
00:11:38,458 --> 00:11:42,541
Through the ventilation opening of the solitary cells

224
00:11:43,750 --> 00:11:48,791
Overlooking the car garage

225
00:11:50,041 --> 00:11:51,041
We could hear clearly

226
00:11:51,125 --> 00:11:52,750
They put him in the van

227
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:55,291
Carrying with them tools for digging graves

228
00:11:56,500 --> 00:11:59,291
I concluded they were going to kill and bury him

229
00:12:00,250 --> 00:12:01,833
After about two hours

230
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:06,750
The members came back with their tools but without Muhannad

231
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:11,666
They were laughing as if returning from an amusing trip

232
00:12:12,833 --> 00:12:14,708
We came to see that as normal

233
00:12:14,875 --> 00:12:17,708
Because it happened regularly from time to time

234
00:12:23,125 --> 00:12:27,250
There were prisoners from the town of Mansoura

235
00:12:30,833 --> 00:12:34,625
They were taken daily for interrogation and torture

236
00:12:34,875 --> 00:12:37,500
Then returned, and that continued for a while

237
00:12:37,958 --> 00:12:40,208
I saw their names on the wall

238
00:12:40,416 --> 00:12:42,625
And learned about their cases

239
00:12:42,916 --> 00:12:44,500
But I didn’t meet any of them because they were far from me

240
00:12:45,208 --> 00:12:47,375
I would hear the sounds of torture when they were taken

241
00:12:47,500 --> 00:12:49,041
But I didn’t know who they were

242
00:12:51,291 --> 00:12:57,500
Once, they took them out before the evening prayer

243
00:12:59,375 --> 00:13:00,791
They took them out one by one

244
00:13:00,958 --> 00:13:02,500
Asking what belongings they had

245
00:13:02,750 --> 00:13:04,875
And if they wanted to send any message to their families

246
00:13:05,875 --> 00:13:08,041
Because the next day

247
00:13:08,458 --> 00:13:10,583
Was the day their sentences would be carried out

248
00:13:11,333 --> 00:13:12,375
Which was execution

249
00:13:12,875 --> 00:13:15,125
And crucifixion in the town of Mansoura

250
00:13:15,833 --> 00:13:18,458
They were sentenced on charges of highway robbery

251
00:13:19,541 --> 00:13:21,541
They were to face the <i>had al-hiraba</i> [punishment for banditry]

252
00:13:21,708 --> 00:13:22,708
Which is execution and crucifixion

253
00:13:23,583 --> 00:13:26,083
They didn’t sleep all night, praying to God

254
00:13:26,208 --> 00:13:28,583
They were taken the next morning

255
00:13:29,833 --> 00:13:31,250
At evening prayer time

256
00:13:31,708 --> 00:13:35,875
ISIS members brought us a newspaper they had issued

257
00:13:36,208 --> 00:13:38,625
It said they had carried out executions

258
00:13:38,750 --> 00:13:40,083
Of eight people

259
00:13:41,041 --> 00:13:43,750
We stayed in shock for several days over what had happened

260
00:13:49,041 --> 00:13:51,125
There was a young man named

261
00:13:51,666 --> 00:13:54,625
Ahmad al-Lajji from Raqqa

262
00:13:54,916 --> 00:13:56,958
And another named Faisal al-Zaher

263
00:13:59,333 --> 00:14:02,083
And another named Ahmad al-Hamoud

264
00:14:02,291 --> 00:14:03,625
He was actually a child, not a young man

265
00:14:04,125 --> 00:14:06,291
They were in solitary cells and we hadn’t spoken before

266
00:14:06,500 --> 00:14:08,333
I didn’t even know they were in prison

267
00:14:09,583 --> 00:14:12,041
They took them and lined them up in front of the group cell

268
00:14:13,375 --> 00:14:16,916
In orange uniforms, with shaved heads and beards

269
00:14:19,500 --> 00:14:21,541
It happened on a Friday morning

270
00:14:22,750 --> 00:14:23,750
They were asked about their charges

271
00:14:23,916 --> 00:14:27,291
All of them were accused of collaborating with the Global Coalition

272
00:14:28,708 --> 00:14:33,625
One of them asked to write a will

273
00:14:33,875 --> 00:14:36,416
So his debts could be paid, but they refused

274
00:14:37,916 --> 00:14:38,958
Then they took them away

275
00:14:39,375 --> 00:14:41,750
I never saw them, only heard their voices

276
00:14:42,083 --> 00:14:43,250
During torture sessions

277
00:14:43,750 --> 00:14:45,416
I didn’t even know their names

278
00:14:45,583 --> 00:14:48,500
Until they were called by name and I saw them then

279
00:14:50,541 --> 00:14:51,583
I used to see their writings on the walls

280
00:14:51,625 --> 00:14:53,291
But I thought they had already been released

281
00:14:54,708 --> 00:14:56,958
Two days later

282
00:14:57,208 --> 00:15:01,708
A young man told me he had seen them killed in Tabqa

283
00:15:02,458 --> 00:15:04,375
Stabbed to death

284
00:15:04,875 --> 00:15:06,750
Then shot afterward

285
00:15:13,750 --> 00:15:15,541
I told him I had seen them only once

286
00:15:15,666 --> 00:15:17,958
Then they brought their magazine

287
00:15:18,583 --> 00:15:23,125
It said they had executed agents of the Coalition

288
00:15:24,833 --> 00:15:29,333
Ahmad al-Lajji, Faisal al-Zaher, and Ahmad al-Hamoud

289
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:35,125
Our spirits would sink again every
time they took prisoners for execution

290
00:15:36,291 --> 00:15:37,291
There was no taste for sleep or food

291
00:15:38,625 --> 00:15:42,208
When we thought of those killed, their families, and their children

292
00:15:42,458 --> 00:15:44,916
It became normal every two or three days

293
00:15:47,250 --> 00:15:50,458
They would take women from the solitary cells

294
00:15:51,041 --> 00:15:55,208
At night, carrying with them grave-digging tools

295
00:15:56,000 --> 00:16:03,208
The vehicles would leave and come back

296
00:16:03,916 --> 00:16:05,083
We saw the members smiling

297
00:16:05,250 --> 00:16:07,833
As if they hadn’t just killed someone

298
00:16:08,958 --> 00:16:11,458
And it kept happening

299
00:16:11,833 --> 00:16:13,583
Every few days they would take one of the women

300
00:16:13,708 --> 00:16:17,666
There were five or six of them, maybe more

301
00:16:23,166 --> 00:16:29,041
After exactly 16 days

302
00:16:30,416 --> 00:16:32,250
My brother was released

303
00:16:33,041 --> 00:16:34,875
Along with the young man who was with me

304
00:16:35,166 --> 00:16:36,833
Who was from Daraa Province

305
00:16:37,166 --> 00:16:38,750
And who used to say that he was with ISIS

306
00:16:39,291 --> 00:16:41,541
He claimed he was one of ISIS’s security members in Daraa

307
00:16:41,750 --> 00:16:44,750
And was detained after being suspected upon arriving in Raqqa

308
00:16:45,333 --> 00:16:47,916
I had nothing personal to talk with him about

309
00:16:48,166 --> 00:16:50,958
The conversations we had were routine and ordinary

310
00:16:51,250 --> 00:16:53,458
They brought in his place a young man from Tabqa

311
00:16:54,708 --> 00:16:56,875
Who stayed with me for three days

312
00:16:57,125 --> 00:16:59,333
I asked him about the situation outside

313
00:16:59,583 --> 00:17:01,083
He had heard about my detention with my family

314
00:17:01,583 --> 00:17:05,666
I asked him who among my relatives
was still imprisoned or had been released

315
00:17:07,125 --> 00:17:09,458
He told me who had been released from prison

316
00:17:09,750 --> 00:17:12,166
According to him, it was me and two of my brothers

317
00:17:12,500 --> 00:17:14,708
My father, and two of my cousins who remained

318
00:17:15,791 --> 00:17:17,250
I could hear the voices of the others in prison

319
00:17:17,416 --> 00:17:19,500
But those whose voices disappeared

320
00:17:19,625 --> 00:17:21,333
I was very worried about what had happened to them

321
00:17:21,541 --> 00:17:24,625
He assured me that all those who had been released were fine

322
00:17:25,666 --> 00:17:31,625
They placed my brother in the prison corridor before sunset

323
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:37,500
During the time when we usually received dinner

324
00:17:41,375 --> 00:17:44,916
My brother started talking to me and asking how I was

325
00:17:45,416 --> 00:17:47,208
Taking advantage of the absence of anyone in the corridor

326
00:17:48,166 --> 00:17:50,000
He told me he was going to be released

327
00:17:50,166 --> 00:17:51,583
Since it was customary to release prisoners

328
00:17:51,875 --> 00:17:54,000
Every Monday and Thursday

329
00:17:54,250 --> 00:17:56,416
But my brother’s release was on a Wednesday

330
00:17:57,875 --> 00:18:01,541
I asked him what he had told them, and he reassured me

331
00:18:01,750 --> 00:18:04,791
Telling me not to worry, that everything
was fine and he would be out soon

332
00:18:05,083 --> 00:18:07,041
My brother was four years older than me

333
00:18:11,750 --> 00:18:15,375
Less than a week later, the interrogator came back to me

334
00:18:15,625 --> 00:18:20,208
He asked, What’s new? Do you need anything?

335
00:18:20,500 --> 00:18:25,583
I said, Nothing new, but I want to see my father, just once

336
00:18:26,458 --> 00:18:29,833
He said, You’ll see him today

337
00:18:30,166 --> 00:18:32,416
So I went to see my father, and through the door

338
00:18:32,791 --> 00:18:34,833
I spoke to him and asked how he was

339
00:18:36,250 --> 00:18:38,541
I reassured him that I was fine

340
00:18:38,791 --> 00:18:42,458
And lifted his spirits a bit so he wouldn’t worry too much about me

341
00:18:42,625 --> 00:18:44,500
Then I returned to my cell after five minutes

342
00:18:50,250 --> 00:18:52,875
About a week later

343
00:18:54,041 --> 00:18:56,458
It seemed to me that a senior ISIS official came to the prison

344
00:18:56,666 --> 00:19:00,500
Because they started cleaning and tidying the facilities

345
00:19:00,958 --> 00:19:02,541
The official made a tour around us

346
00:19:02,750 --> 00:19:05,000
Asking, What’s your name? What’s your case?

347
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:08,125
He asked me, Do you need anything?

348
00:19:09,083 --> 00:19:11,916
I explained my situation and asked about my fate

349
00:19:12,125 --> 00:19:14,083
He said, Don’t worry, everything’s fine

350
00:19:15,250 --> 00:19:16,250
Then he repeated, Do you want anything else?

351
00:19:16,416 --> 00:19:17,416
I said, I want to see my father

352
00:19:18,333 --> 00:19:19,750
He asked, When was the last time you saw him?

353
00:19:19,958 --> 00:19:21,791
I answered, Once, and for five minutes

354
00:19:22,541 --> 00:19:23,500
He said, Alright

355
00:19:23,750 --> 00:19:28,708
Then placed me with my father in the
same group cell, where I found him alone

356
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:32,333
The official continued his tour

357
00:19:32,500 --> 00:19:34,500
And we could hear the voices of my brother and cousins

358
00:19:34,666 --> 00:19:36,208
As he asked them about their needs

359
00:19:37,333 --> 00:19:40,958
When I saw my father, he hugged
me and started crying. He was fasting

360
00:19:42,083 --> 00:19:45,000
It was Thursday, and we broke our fast together

361
00:19:46,416 --> 00:19:48,625
We didn’t sleep all night

362
00:19:48,833 --> 00:19:50,500
Because of our long conversation
and how much we missed each other

363
00:19:50,833 --> 00:19:54,458
We tried to lift our spirits and comfort each other

364
00:19:54,833 --> 00:19:56,958
We talked about the charges brought against us

365
00:19:57,250 --> 00:19:59,250
My father’s charge was that he once said

366
00:19:59,500 --> 00:20:02,708
That if a military operation began against ISIS in the area

367
00:20:02,916 --> 00:20:05,916
He would be ready to arm 500 fighters

368
00:20:06,625 --> 00:20:09,166
Which was, of course, a fabricated and false accusation

369
00:20:09,541 --> 00:20:15,000
They demanded he bring 500 rifles

370
00:20:17,125 --> 00:20:19,000
My father, in turn, demanded

371
00:20:19,291 --> 00:20:20,666
That they bring witnesses to these accusations

372
00:20:21,083 --> 00:20:22,583
They told him, Your witness is here

373
00:20:23,125 --> 00:20:24,666
He said, Bring him, I have no problem

374
00:20:25,041 --> 00:20:26,708
After the interrogation ended

375
00:20:27,500 --> 00:20:31,458
One of the prisoners told him the name of the witness

376
00:20:31,791 --> 00:20:34,000
And informed my father about it

377
00:20:34,583 --> 00:20:37,125
My father told his fellow prisoners

378
00:20:37,291 --> 00:20:39,500
About the accusation against him

379
00:20:39,791 --> 00:20:41,291
And that there was a witness

380
00:20:42,083 --> 00:20:44,166
He repeatedly asked for the witness
to be brought, but they never did

381
00:20:44,416 --> 00:20:46,166
When one of my father’s cellmates was released

382
00:20:46,250 --> 00:20:47,375
He told the story to the supposed witness

383
00:20:47,500 --> 00:20:49,208
Who later came to the prison

384
00:20:49,416 --> 00:20:52,541
And confirmed that he had not witnessed what my father said

385
00:20:53,291 --> 00:20:55,666
That the entire accusation had no basis in truth

386
00:20:56,375 --> 00:20:58,041
But ISIS members expelled him

387
00:20:58,166 --> 00:20:59,916
Telling him that it was none of his concern

388
00:21:00,500 --> 00:21:03,625
It became clear that the accusation was fabricated

389
00:21:04,125 --> 00:21:05,833
And my father’s imprisonment was purely arbitrary

390
00:21:11,333 --> 00:21:12,750
They took me for interrogation

391
00:21:14,041 --> 00:21:17,041
And asked, Do you need anything?

392
00:21:17,375 --> 00:21:19,250
I felt then that they wanted to release me

393
00:21:19,458 --> 00:21:20,708
I said, No, nothing

394
00:21:21,208 --> 00:21:26,083
He said, The method of interrogation will completely change

395
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:29,125
If you have something to say

396
00:21:29,291 --> 00:21:31,750
Now is the time before they use another method

397
00:21:31,916 --> 00:21:34,083
I told him I had nothing to add

398
00:21:34,250 --> 00:21:35,833
He was expecting me to talk about weapons and such

399
00:21:36,625 --> 00:21:37,958
But I assured him I had no weapons

400
00:21:38,583 --> 00:21:42,583
And that I wasn’t the person they were looking for

401
00:21:44,125 --> 00:21:45,375
He was the one responsible for what you accuse me of

402
00:21:45,958 --> 00:21:47,250
And he had been imprisoned by you before

403
00:21:47,875 --> 00:21:49,375
And it was you who released him

404
00:21:49,458 --> 00:21:52,625
So you are responsible for this mistake, not me

405
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:55,583
He said, Alright, and sent me back

406
00:21:55,750 --> 00:21:58,791
After 10 minutes, I heard the sound of torture

407
00:21:59,458 --> 00:22:01,833
It was one of my cousins, I recognized his voice well

408
00:22:02,625 --> 00:22:06,041
They kept torturing him for two hours

409
00:22:07,750 --> 00:22:08,833
Then they summoned me for interrogation

410
00:22:08,916 --> 00:22:11,291
I realized that my turn for torture had come

411
00:22:11,583 --> 00:22:13,583
He repeated his question, Anything
new? I repeated my answer, Nothing

412
00:22:13,833 --> 00:22:17,166
They started torturing me immediately, for half an hour or an hour

413
00:22:17,833 --> 00:22:20,583
They kept torturing me until I lost consciousness

414
00:22:22,083 --> 00:22:24,458
Then they splashed me with water to wake me up

415
00:22:24,625 --> 00:22:26,583
I could hear them, but I couldn’t walk

416
00:22:27,125 --> 00:22:28,541
So they sent me back to the solitary cell

417
00:22:28,666 --> 00:22:32,375
I heard them call for Abdullah Salamah

418
00:22:32,833 --> 00:22:34,875
Both my brother and my cousin shared

419
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:36,000
The same name

420
00:22:37,083 --> 00:22:39,291
He asked him, Are you Abu Islam? He answered, No

421
00:22:39,500 --> 00:22:41,500
So I knew they wanted my cousin

422
00:22:42,208 --> 00:22:45,666
They took him and repeated the torture on him

423
00:22:45,875 --> 00:22:47,333
He couldn’t bear it because he had asthma

424
00:22:47,458 --> 00:22:49,916
He fainted after half an hour or less

425
00:22:50,708 --> 00:22:53,625
They splashed him with water. I
heard his voice and felt reassured

426
00:22:54,750 --> 00:22:55,916
Because I had been so worried about him

427
00:22:57,166 --> 00:22:58,458
Then they took my brother for interrogation

428
00:23:00,125 --> 00:23:02,708
I started waiting to hear the sounds of torture

429
00:23:02,875 --> 00:23:04,333
Thinking they would do to him what they had done to us

430
00:23:04,416 --> 00:23:05,250
But they didn’t torture him

431
00:23:05,375 --> 00:23:07,250
Even though he stayed there for three or four hours

432
00:23:08,291 --> 00:23:10,291
They sent him back without torturing him

433
00:23:10,708 --> 00:23:12,708
Torture became a daily routine for us

434
00:23:13,416 --> 00:23:14,875
We got used to it

435
00:23:15,291 --> 00:23:16,666
Whenever we heard someone being tortured

436
00:23:16,791 --> 00:23:19,250
We knew our turn was coming

437
00:23:20,750 --> 00:23:22,416
Once, I was asleep one afternoon

438
00:23:23,458 --> 00:23:25,666
I woke up to the sound of one of my cousins being tortured

439
00:23:25,875 --> 00:23:28,583
I knew things had become serious

440
00:23:30,041 --> 00:23:31,625
He was tortured for three hours

441
00:23:32,208 --> 00:23:34,833
Until he lost consciousness and they brought him back

442
00:23:35,041 --> 00:23:37,541
I heard the interrogator say to him

443
00:23:37,750 --> 00:23:39,875
Bring me Faraj Salamah

444
00:23:41,541 --> 00:23:44,916
He interrogated me for a short while

445
00:23:45,166 --> 00:23:47,916
I was waiting for the torture to start

446
00:23:48,166 --> 00:23:49,500
Expecting any blow

447
00:23:49,666 --> 00:23:51,166
Because I was blindfolded and handcuffed

448
00:23:52,416 --> 00:23:54,750
Then the interrogator ordered that I be
tortured by suspension [<i>shabeh</i>]

449
00:23:55,666 --> 00:23:57,041
So I remained suspended

450
00:23:57,958 --> 00:24:02,291
I realized that my cousin hadn’t been tortured again

451
00:24:02,583 --> 00:24:07,333
Because of his illness and the interrogator’s fear of the consequences

452
00:24:07,625 --> 00:24:09,500
Since my cousin’s condition was severe

453
00:24:10,250 --> 00:24:11,875
He postponed his torture session

454
00:24:13,125 --> 00:24:15,458
As for me, I remained suspended for nine hours

455
00:24:16,625 --> 00:24:17,833
Then they sent me back

456
00:24:18,791 --> 00:24:21,166
I was reassured about my cousin after midnight

457
00:24:21,583 --> 00:24:23,166
When I called out to him

458
00:24:23,333 --> 00:24:26,166
He answered that he was fine, praise God

459
00:24:27,541 --> 00:24:29,958
Since then, they slightly changed their approach

460
00:24:31,583 --> 00:24:32,625
They would take us for interrogation from time to time

461
00:24:32,750 --> 00:24:36,333
But they stopped torturing us, or postponed it

462
00:24:43,541 --> 00:24:45,291
At exactly 12 midnight

463
00:24:46,666 --> 00:24:50,875
We heard a sound in the wall near the window

464
00:24:51,250 --> 00:24:54,750
It seemed like an escape attempt was happening

465
00:24:56,041 --> 00:25:00,916
We stayed anxious because we
didn’t know what was happening outside

466
00:25:01,833 --> 00:25:05,166
When I was in the far group cell

467
00:25:05,666 --> 00:25:09,000
I knew there was a place easy to escape from

468
00:25:10,041 --> 00:25:12,333
The prison was basically a basement

469
00:25:12,541 --> 00:25:15,375
With a small breathing window above

470
00:25:15,791 --> 00:25:19,000
Completely reinforced with iron protection

471
00:25:19,875 --> 00:25:21,250
But that group cell

472
00:25:21,500 --> 00:25:23,208
Had an external staircase

473
00:25:24,083 --> 00:25:25,333
Which they had recently sealed off

474
00:25:25,916 --> 00:25:27,500
Using concrete blocks

475
00:25:27,583 --> 00:25:30,958
It was sealed tightly

476
00:25:32,500 --> 00:25:33,750
But if someone thought and worked carefully

477
00:25:33,833 --> 00:25:34,958
It was possible to escape from there

478
00:25:35,708 --> 00:25:37,250
I noticed a solid iron object outside

479
00:25:38,583 --> 00:25:40,625
When my cousin and I were preparing to escape

480
00:25:40,750 --> 00:25:42,625
During a time when my relatives were being released regularly

481
00:25:42,750 --> 00:25:45,291
We thought our turn for release was coming soon

482
00:25:47,291 --> 00:25:48,958
But we decided to escape

483
00:25:49,208 --> 00:25:50,750
Unfortunately, they transferred us to a different cell

484
00:25:50,875 --> 00:25:52,541
When I was with my father, I told him

485
00:25:52,625 --> 00:25:55,125
That we had planned to escape from that group cell

486
00:26:00,416 --> 00:26:03,625
My father was with a young man named Ahmad Seno

487
00:26:04,375 --> 00:26:06,625
And another young man named Hamad

488
00:26:10,416 --> 00:26:13,166
I had spoken to them about my plan to escape through that cell

489
00:26:13,958 --> 00:26:15,458
It seems they remembered my words exactly

490
00:26:15,541 --> 00:26:17,666
Saying, This is the cell he talked about

491
00:26:17,916 --> 00:26:22,000
And that this was where the
external door had recently been sealed

492
00:26:22,750 --> 00:26:24,500
They also saw the same iron piece

493
00:26:24,666 --> 00:26:26,541
I had told them about, so they decided to escape

494
00:26:28,208 --> 00:26:29,666
I realized that they were escaping

495
00:26:30,208 --> 00:26:31,583
The next morning after the escape

496
00:26:33,125 --> 00:26:36,500
There was great chaos inside the prison

497
00:26:36,666 --> 00:26:38,958
They distributed special prison uniforms to us

498
00:26:39,125 --> 00:26:40,958
They took all our civilian clothes

499
00:26:41,583 --> 00:26:42,708
They also gave us numbers

500
00:26:43,208 --> 00:26:44,916
And searched for any iron objects

501
00:26:45,416 --> 00:26:48,666
They installed surveillance cameras in the prison

502
00:26:50,750 --> 00:26:52,625
Then one of them came and asked me, What’s your name?

503
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:54,583
I answered, Faraj Salamah

504
00:26:54,916 --> 00:26:56,958
He asked, Is your father’s name Khalaf?

505
00:26:57,125 --> 00:26:59,708
I said yes, and he told me that
my father had escaped from prison

506
00:27:00,625 --> 00:27:02,875
I had suspected that all that noise was because of an escape

507
00:27:03,083 --> 00:27:06,000
And that the escape had happened from our same group cell

508
00:27:06,166 --> 00:27:07,666
But I didn’t know who they were at the time

509
00:27:07,916 --> 00:27:10,208
Yet when my father’s voice grew distant, I thought

510
00:27:10,291 --> 00:27:11,750
He must have been in that faraway cell

511
00:27:12,083 --> 00:27:14,166
I pretended to the one asking that I
was upset about my father’s escape

512
00:27:14,291 --> 00:27:18,625
Because no charges had been
proven against us for three months

513
00:27:19,291 --> 00:27:22,250
My father had endured prison and
nothing had been proven against him

514
00:27:22,666 --> 00:27:26,625
So it didn’t make sense for him to escape and leave us behind

515
00:27:27,833 --> 00:27:29,958
Inside, I prayed to God to help him succeed

516
00:27:31,625 --> 00:27:35,083
He told me they would catch him wherever he was

517
00:27:35,291 --> 00:27:39,083
Whether in Turkey or in Germany

518
00:27:41,291 --> 00:27:43,666
I told him I wasn’t responsible for his escape

519
00:27:43,791 --> 00:27:45,375
I was in one group cell and he was in another

520
00:27:45,583 --> 00:27:46,916
He said, You’re not to blame

521
00:27:47,291 --> 00:27:48,833
What we want is for you to call your uncles

522
00:27:49,708 --> 00:27:52,541
And tell them you’ll be killed if your father doesn’t return

523
00:27:53,666 --> 00:27:56,916
I told him I didn’t know their numbers

524
00:27:57,041 --> 00:27:58,500
But he kept insisting

525
00:27:58,583 --> 00:28:00,750
So I said, As you wish, but bring me one of their numbers

526
00:28:00,958 --> 00:28:07,125
A day and then two passed without him coming back

527
00:28:12,791 --> 00:28:15,291
The Tower was made up of 12 floors

528
00:28:15,375 --> 00:28:18,375
Destroyed from the outside by Assad regime airstrikes

529
00:28:19,083 --> 00:28:23,541
They had built a prison in the basement

530
00:28:23,833 --> 00:28:26,166
With multiple solitary cells

531
00:28:26,333 --> 00:28:29,791
And another section they called the disciplinary cells

532
00:28:31,041 --> 00:28:34,125
Which was itself an inseparable part of the solitary area

533
00:28:34,625 --> 00:28:35,708
There was another section for group cells

534
00:28:37,041 --> 00:28:41,083
A corridor separated the group cells from the solitary ones

535
00:28:41,583 --> 00:28:43,708
And there was a section designated for the disciplinary cells

536
00:28:43,833 --> 00:28:46,000
In addition to faraway, unknown cells

537
00:28:51,791 --> 00:28:54,000
There were many people inside

538
00:28:54,083 --> 00:28:55,625
I’ll now list the ones I remember

539
00:28:56,333 --> 00:28:59,500
Among my relatives were my brothers

540
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:03,458
Abdullah, Abdul Hakim, and Muhammad al-Salamah

541
00:29:04,041 --> 00:29:05,416
And my father, Khalaf al-Salamah

542
00:29:06,291 --> 00:29:08,125
And my cousin Abdullah Hassan al-Salamah

543
00:29:08,833 --> 00:29:11,333
And my other cousins

544
00:29:11,541 --> 00:29:14,333
Abdul Musleh Hassan al-Ibrahim

545
00:29:14,833 --> 00:29:17,458
And Hammouda and Ahmad Hassan al-Ibrahim

546
00:29:17,916 --> 00:29:19,750
And Abdul Hakim Hassan al-Ibrahim

547
00:29:20,541 --> 00:29:22,541
Aziz Hassan al-Ibrahim

548
00:29:25,916 --> 00:29:28,416
Ahmad Hassan—I think I already mentioned him

549
00:29:29,958 --> 00:29:31,708
And Faraj Hassan al-Ibrahim

550
00:29:33,250 --> 00:29:36,500
And their sons, Hassan Ibrahim al-Hassan

551
00:29:37,166 --> 00:29:38,500
Faraj Ibrahim al-Hassan

552
00:29:39,041 --> 00:29:40,791
And Muhammad Faraj al-Hassan

553
00:29:42,208 --> 00:29:45,541
And Muhammad Abdul Fattah al-Oweihi, my cousin

554
00:29:46,333 --> 00:29:49,250
And Kamal Abdul Fattah al-Oweihi

555
00:29:50,541 --> 00:29:54,750
From Jarniya, there was Walid al-Haji

556
00:29:55,250 --> 00:29:57,666
And Muasstam and Hamada al-Haji

557
00:30:02,916 --> 00:30:07,000
There was also a young man named
Anis, a relative of ours from the area

558
00:30:08,625 --> 00:30:12,916
As well as others who had been imprisoned before us

559
00:30:13,166 --> 00:30:14,583
Including Muhannad al-Raji

560
00:30:16,041 --> 00:30:18,291
Ahmad al-Laji and Faisal al-Zahir

561
00:30:18,708 --> 00:30:19,708
Ahmad al-Hamoud

562
00:30:20,416 --> 00:30:24,125
And people from Raqqa Prison, among them Ahmad Sinu

563
00:30:24,708 --> 00:30:26,125
And a young man named Hamad

564
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:30,833
And young men from the al-Hutayl clan in Mansoura

565
00:30:32,125 --> 00:30:34,166
I don’t remember their names

566
00:30:34,458 --> 00:30:38,250
Because their names were similar to ours

567
00:30:38,416 --> 00:30:40,750
And I started getting confused from so many names

568
00:30:41,166 --> 00:30:46,458
There were also friends of mine in prison

569
00:30:46,916 --> 00:30:49,000
Harith Haj Abdul Sheikh

570
00:30:49,500 --> 00:30:52,666
And Faisal Saad Rajoub from Homs

571
00:30:53,333 --> 00:30:56,958
And Khaled al-Harbi, a young man from Tabqa

572
00:30:57,916 --> 00:31:01,500
And a young man from Rural Aleppo named Alaa

573
00:31:02,041 --> 00:31:04,500
But he was killed in prison

574
00:31:05,416 --> 00:31:07,166
There were also foreign prisoners

575
00:31:07,291 --> 00:31:10,916
Affiliated with ISIS, but they never told me their names

576
00:31:11,083 --> 00:31:13,000
They all went by noms de guerre like Abu so-and-so

577
00:31:13,125 --> 00:31:15,833
Among them were Saudis

578
00:31:16,625 --> 00:31:20,250
And a Lebanese-born man with German citizenship

579
00:31:20,625 --> 00:31:25,583
He had been wounded by a gunshot from one of his comrades

580
00:31:25,833 --> 00:31:27,208
And had metal rods in his body

581
00:31:27,625 --> 00:31:30,416
There were six foreign prisoners in total

582
00:31:31,250 --> 00:31:34,333
Because they were against the idea of establishing the Islamic State

583
00:31:34,500 --> 00:31:37,500
They had criticized it, so they were imprisoned

584
00:31:44,375 --> 00:31:47,583
The general official was called Abu Luqman

585
00:31:47,958 --> 00:31:49,625
His name was Ibrahim al-Shawakh

586
00:31:50,541 --> 00:31:53,708
From the town of al-Sahl in Raqqa Province

587
00:31:54,250 --> 00:31:55,666
The internal official

588
00:31:56,125 --> 00:31:58,000
Was Mahmoud al-Ibrahim al-Dakhil

589
00:31:58,291 --> 00:32:00,041
His mother’s name was Shamsa

590
00:32:00,500 --> 00:32:03,875
From the town of Mansoura in the Tabqa countryside

591
00:32:04,125 --> 00:32:05,625
He was originally from the al-Bou Masra clan

592
00:32:05,666 --> 00:32:10,666
He was responsible for interrogations
in Tabqa and its countryside

593
00:32:11,500 --> 00:32:16,583
The official in charge of the jailers was a Saudi man

594
00:32:18,458 --> 00:32:19,500
Named Abu Nayef

595
00:32:21,541 --> 00:32:24,000
He was responsible for the jailers and the prison’s cleanliness

596
00:32:24,208 --> 00:32:26,333
The jailers were from the same area, from Tabqa

597
00:32:26,958 --> 00:32:29,875
One was called Abu Abdullah

598
00:32:30,416 --> 00:32:32,083
Another was called Abu Zaid

599
00:32:32,958 --> 00:32:34,791
And Abdul Muin

600
00:32:35,625 --> 00:32:39,041
And a young man nicknamed Abu Abdu

601
00:32:40,625 --> 00:32:44,166
Two of them were present, and two were absent

602
00:32:44,333 --> 00:32:48,500
They took shifts for irregular periods, from days up to a week

603
00:32:53,625 --> 00:32:57,750
At first, the approach was calm and smooth

604
00:32:58,833 --> 00:33:01,291
The interrogator found nothing he was looking for

605
00:33:01,750 --> 00:33:05,250
Then he began torturing by beating

606
00:33:05,958 --> 00:33:09,791
All over the body with a hose or a stick

607
00:33:10,041 --> 00:33:11,791
Even if our bodies broke under torture

608
00:33:12,083 --> 00:33:14,583
Because more than one prisoner suffered fractures as a result

609
00:33:17,583 --> 00:33:18,958
He kept beating continuously

610
00:33:19,083 --> 00:33:23,791
As long as the person did not lose consciousness

611
00:33:24,750 --> 00:33:27,291
If he found no result, he tried
the suspension [<i>shabeh</i>] method

612
00:33:28,041 --> 00:33:31,333
He lifted the person using the <i>balingo</i>
[hoist] by his hands

613
00:33:32,166 --> 00:33:33,250
So that his feet did not touch the ground

614
00:33:33,583 --> 00:33:36,666
Which forced the prisoner

615
00:33:36,833 --> 00:33:40,125
To confess to whatever the interrogator wanted

616
00:33:40,500 --> 00:33:43,041
Even if the person had done nothing against them at all

617
00:33:43,375 --> 00:33:46,250
We said there was beating and suspension

618
00:33:46,625 --> 00:33:49,250
As for the women, we heard their screams

619
00:33:49,375 --> 00:33:50,833
Without knowing their method of torture

620
00:33:50,958 --> 00:33:52,625
Without hearing the sounds of beating

621
00:33:52,791 --> 00:33:55,166
Or knowing their style of interrogation with women

622
00:33:55,333 --> 00:33:57,291
But interrogations always took place after midnight

623
00:33:57,916 --> 00:34:00,333
And lasted for around three hours

624
00:34:00,666 --> 00:34:03,875
Torture included everyone without exception

625
00:34:04,083 --> 00:34:07,000
And it was done according to the charges brought against them

626
00:34:07,208 --> 00:34:09,250
And based on confessions

627
00:34:10,166 --> 00:34:13,125
Anyone with serious charges

628
00:34:14,541 --> 00:34:18,083
Was tortured by all means until he spoke

629
00:34:18,250 --> 00:34:21,000
They continued even if it led to death

630
00:34:21,250 --> 00:34:23,291
Once, they tortured a man

631
00:34:23,625 --> 00:34:25,041
Before I was detained

632
00:34:25,458 --> 00:34:27,500
His name was Ammar, from al-Baasi village

633
00:34:27,625 --> 00:34:29,291
They kept torturing him until he died

634
00:34:29,875 --> 00:34:31,708
Without extracting any confession

635
00:34:32,291 --> 00:34:34,833
So I realized they had no problem with a prisoner dying

636
00:34:34,958 --> 00:34:36,000
Depending on his case

637
00:34:36,541 --> 00:34:37,583
No problem

638
00:34:43,166 --> 00:34:47,958
Psychological torture was exhausting and constant

639
00:34:48,666 --> 00:34:51,916
We were kept in the disciplinary cell

640
00:34:52,208 --> 00:34:55,208
They told us, You will not live long. Repent to your Lord

641
00:34:55,583 --> 00:34:59,416
And said things like, Your days are
numbered. Don’t think of getting out at all

642
00:35:00,041 --> 00:35:02,166
There were also people

643
00:35:03,041 --> 00:35:06,750
Among the prisoners whom they dressed in yellow clothes

644
00:35:07,541 --> 00:35:09,500
Their execution outfit

645
00:35:10,083 --> 00:35:12,000
They shaved their hair and beards

646
00:35:12,250 --> 00:35:17,291
Reenacting the steps of execution preparation

647
00:35:17,708 --> 00:35:20,708
Assuming he was not Muslim and they had the right to kill him

648
00:35:20,875 --> 00:35:25,083
Which was sometimes more terrifying
and painful than physical torture

649
00:35:29,958 --> 00:35:31,875
They gave us books

650
00:35:32,583 --> 00:35:35,083
Religious books and the Quran

651
00:35:35,541 --> 00:35:37,125
And newspapers issued by them

652
00:35:37,375 --> 00:35:39,291
We looked for outside news

653
00:35:39,375 --> 00:35:41,250
Though we knew it was not reliable

654
00:35:41,375 --> 00:35:44,000
The news was scarce and limited to their achievements

655
00:35:44,375 --> 00:35:46,166
So we had to read the books

656
00:35:46,875 --> 00:35:48,916
Willingly, not by force

657
00:35:49,583 --> 00:35:53,000
We also communicated with other group cells

658
00:35:53,166 --> 00:35:57,000
Through the electricity and water pipes

659
00:35:57,291 --> 00:36:01,000
To ask newly arrived prisoners about outside news

660
00:36:01,500 --> 00:36:04,583
Relations were good because we were ignorant of our fate

661
00:36:04,875 --> 00:36:08,583
If death came, we were all in the same boat

662
00:36:09,208 --> 00:36:11,625
We had a small glimmer of hope

663
00:36:11,958 --> 00:36:13,666
That we might see each other outside prison

664
00:36:13,875 --> 00:36:18,375
Our relationship was good, even more than brotherly

665
00:36:18,541 --> 00:36:21,125
We refused when they offered to show us their ISIS videos

666
00:36:21,416 --> 00:36:25,000
Because all their productions showed the killing of prisoners

667
00:36:25,375 --> 00:36:26,708
As well as battles

668
00:36:26,916 --> 00:36:28,958
All scenes of killing and violence

669
00:36:29,083 --> 00:36:31,750
We had absolutely no need to see anything like that

670
00:36:32,375 --> 00:36:35,958
There was a routine every Monday and Thursday

671
00:36:36,625 --> 00:36:39,000
Fasting was obligatory

672
00:36:39,291 --> 00:36:41,125
They prepared a meal

673
00:36:41,625 --> 00:36:45,083
Of <i>suhur</i> [pre-dawn meal] on Wednesday night

674
00:36:45,791 --> 00:36:49,791
So we could fast on Thursday

675
00:36:50,583 --> 00:36:53,500
On regular days, there were two
meals, one in the morning and another

676
00:36:53,625 --> 00:36:57,875
At or just before sunset prayer

677
00:36:58,916 --> 00:37:03,375
They sometimes left some food

678
00:37:03,583 --> 00:37:06,083
So if we got hungry at night, we could eat

679
00:37:08,000 --> 00:37:10,958
Every Friday morning

680
00:37:11,333 --> 00:37:17,125
We personally cleaned the group cell

681
00:37:17,500 --> 00:37:22,375
And the corridor between the group cells and the solitary cells

682
00:37:23,125 --> 00:37:26,041
It was mandatory for the prisoners

683
00:37:26,291 --> 00:37:31,416
That two or three of them go out to clean the group cell

684
00:37:36,875 --> 00:37:40,125
They offered to cancel half of my sentence

685
00:37:40,375 --> 00:37:42,750
In exchange for me handing over my
brother who had not been detained

686
00:37:43,166 --> 00:37:46,250
He would come in, and I would be released instead

687
00:37:46,583 --> 00:37:49,666
I claimed that our relationship was normal

688
00:37:49,875 --> 00:37:51,958
And I did not expect him to come for me

689
00:37:52,083 --> 00:37:53,416
If he was outside the area

690
00:37:53,791 --> 00:37:55,000
And that it was their mistake

691
00:37:55,125 --> 00:37:58,208
Because they had already detained
him earlier on multiple charges

692
00:37:58,500 --> 00:38:02,125
And still could not get anything from him

693
00:38:02,375 --> 00:38:04,541
So I was not obliged to do that

694
00:38:06,083 --> 00:38:08,500
When I was released, they tried to bargain with me to join them

695
00:38:08,791 --> 00:38:11,666
At the same time a Syrian regime convoy arrived

696
00:38:12,416 --> 00:38:13,625
Along with the Russians

697
00:38:14,083 --> 00:38:15,583
On their way to Tabqa city

698
00:38:16,333 --> 00:38:20,166
They tried to convince me to take a weapon from them

699
00:38:20,333 --> 00:38:23,875
And fight alongside them if we shared the same cause

700
00:38:24,041 --> 00:38:26,291
As proof of my loyalty to them

701
00:38:28,500 --> 00:38:31,750
Interviewer: And how did they react to your refusal?

702
00:38:32,166 --> 00:38:33,833
Of course, I refused in an indirect way

703
00:38:33,958 --> 00:38:36,250
By saying that I was the youngest in my family

704
00:38:36,333 --> 00:38:40,291
And that my mother would never abandon me after prison

705
00:38:40,500 --> 00:38:42,333
And I had no idea how her health was

706
00:38:42,458 --> 00:38:45,166
So how could I get out and take up arms immediately

707
00:38:50,500 --> 00:38:54,208
After I completed four months in prison

708
00:38:56,833 --> 00:38:59,375
The interrogator came to me and opened the shutter

709
00:38:59,500 --> 00:39:01,791
He said, Come here! What’s your name? I answered him

710
00:39:02,875 --> 00:39:05,875
He asked, How long have you been here? I said, Four months

711
00:39:06,625 --> 00:39:08,750
He said, Fine, you’ve been here too long, we’ll release you

712
00:39:09,833 --> 00:39:13,166
And you must tell your father to come back

713
00:39:13,291 --> 00:39:17,875
Because by escaping, he proved the charge against himself

714
00:39:18,625 --> 00:39:21,500
I said, Since you’re sure he’s innocent

715
00:39:21,625 --> 00:39:24,208
Why did he stay three months until he had to escape

716
00:39:25,083 --> 00:39:27,458
Why didn’t you release him then?

717
00:39:29,875 --> 00:39:34,875
He said, The point is to tell him to
come back, there’s nothing against him

718
00:39:35,083 --> 00:39:40,500
Better than traveling to Azaz, Qamishli, or Turkey

719
00:39:41,208 --> 00:39:42,333
I said, God willing

720
00:39:42,416 --> 00:39:43,416
So I could get out of prison afterward

721
00:39:44,750 --> 00:39:46,500
Before leaving, I asked about my brother, and he said

722
00:39:46,625 --> 00:39:49,916
He must pay 10,000 dollars to be released

723
00:39:51,458 --> 00:39:54,708
Plus another 10,000 dollars for my cousin

724
00:39:55,875 --> 00:39:59,166
The interrogator told me that once they had received the money

725
00:39:59,375 --> 00:40:00,541
They would release them immediately

726
00:40:00,666 --> 00:40:04,291
So I secured the amount for my brother that night

727
00:40:05,458 --> 00:40:07,458
And I went to them after Maghrib prayer

728
00:40:07,750 --> 00:40:09,750
Right after I had secured the money

729
00:40:10,583 --> 00:40:14,250
But they didn’t receive me and told me to come back the next day

730
00:40:14,750 --> 00:40:17,208
Because there were no visits at night

731
00:40:17,833 --> 00:40:18,833
So I came back the next day

732
00:40:20,333 --> 00:40:22,166
I handed over the money, and my brother was released

733
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:28,250
Some time after my release

734
00:40:28,333 --> 00:40:32,083
ISIS members returned to search for my father

735
00:40:32,291 --> 00:40:34,291
Every day or two, they came back

736
00:40:34,416 --> 00:40:36,083
They knew my brother had fled to Qamishli

737
00:40:36,541 --> 00:40:38,500
But my father hadn’t left the area

738
00:40:39,041 --> 00:40:42,250
And ISIS members knew that

739
00:40:42,375 --> 00:40:44,208
So they came regularly asking about him

740
00:40:45,958 --> 00:40:47,541
And about my brother too

741
00:40:47,916 --> 00:40:51,583
They also used to summon my other brother

742
00:40:52,916 --> 00:40:55,291
To ask him about my father and my brother

743
00:40:55,458 --> 00:40:58,166
When they would come, and
which relatives we were in touch with

744
00:40:58,375 --> 00:41:00,125
They pressured us heavily

745
00:41:00,583 --> 00:41:02,958
Trying to make us leave the area

746
00:41:03,083 --> 00:41:05,250
They clearly didn’t want us there at all

747
00:41:07,583 --> 00:41:09,791
They repeated the same interrogations with my nephew too

748
00:41:10,458 --> 00:41:14,000
They also took our ID cards

749
00:41:14,750 --> 00:41:18,250
From me, my brothers, and my cousins, and never returned them

750
00:41:18,750 --> 00:41:22,125
But they did give us back our mobile phones

751
00:41:22,333 --> 00:41:24,000
They said it was forbidden to return IDs

752
00:41:24,166 --> 00:41:25,708
We followed up with them about the IDs

753
00:41:25,875 --> 00:41:27,791
Until they started threatening to imprison us if we asked again

754
00:41:27,916 --> 00:41:29,541
They told us to forget about them

755
00:41:30,625 --> 00:41:35,041
Then I realized they might use the IDs to escape someday

756
00:41:39,083 --> 00:41:44,333
So we stopped asking about them altogether

757
00:41:45,333 --> 00:41:48,541
They issued us identification cards instead

758
00:41:52,541 --> 00:41:55,291
After we had attended a sharia course

759
00:41:55,416 --> 00:41:58,625
To receive the ID card that became mandatory

760
00:41:59,333 --> 00:42:00,916
We started showing them at checkpoints

761
00:42:01,041 --> 00:42:02,416
Unable to move without them

762
00:42:07,833 --> 00:42:11,916
All the prisoners’ stories were sad

763
00:42:12,208 --> 00:42:14,625
Especially those whose children had been killed

764
00:42:14,833 --> 00:42:16,250
Or who had left orphans behind

765
00:42:17,458 --> 00:42:19,000
There was a young man named Abu Madian

766
00:42:19,333 --> 00:42:20,333
From the town of Mansoura

767
00:42:20,750 --> 00:42:24,916
We used to notice his written memories of his son

768
00:42:25,125 --> 00:42:27,625
In every solitary or group cell we passed through

769
00:42:27,791 --> 00:42:29,708
He would express his feelings and longing

770
00:42:29,833 --> 00:42:32,208
Madian, my dear, I never got enough of you, mourning his son

771
00:42:32,583 --> 00:42:34,833
As if he knew he would never see him again

772
00:42:35,208 --> 00:42:37,333
He was the one who made us feel the saddest

773
00:42:37,458 --> 00:42:39,208
Even though I never met him

774
00:42:39,291 --> 00:42:41,875
I’m still affected by him to this day

775
00:42:43,666 --> 00:42:46,541
Another young man was named Faisal Saad Rajoub

776
00:42:46,708 --> 00:42:47,708
From Homs

777
00:42:48,500 --> 00:42:51,666
He stayed under the siege of Homs even after his family left

778
00:42:51,958 --> 00:42:54,291
Resisting there for about four years

779
00:42:54,875 --> 00:42:57,083
He left through the United Nations

780
00:42:58,416 --> 00:43:00,916
He tried every way to reach his mother but failed

781
00:43:01,083 --> 00:43:03,500
So he was forced to join ISIS

782
00:43:03,583 --> 00:43:07,333
He tried to go to Turkey to see her but couldn’t

783
00:43:08,166 --> 00:43:09,291
During his torture

784
00:43:11,083 --> 00:43:14,625
He kept screaming for his mother

785
00:43:14,833 --> 00:43:17,875
Begging her forgiveness because he couldn’t see her

786
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:19,833
Or reach her

787
00:43:20,083 --> 00:43:22,875
While she was suffering from heart disease

788
00:43:23,541 --> 00:43:25,791
He was deeply affected by his mother’s condition

789
00:43:26,125 --> 00:43:28,333
His mind was preoccupied

790
00:43:29,541 --> 00:43:32,250
Thinking how his mother would
take the news of his death later

791
00:43:37,375 --> 00:43:39,500
Since my release, I’ve been trying

792
00:43:40,000 --> 00:43:42,791
To escape the area completely

793
00:43:42,958 --> 00:43:44,500
I was in a very difficult mental state

794
00:43:45,625 --> 00:43:48,500
I remained affected until ISIS left the area

795
00:43:48,750 --> 00:43:51,000
Of course, I didn’t wait for them

796
00:43:51,125 --> 00:43:52,375
I was the one who fled

797
00:43:52,791 --> 00:43:55,458
To the town of al-Bab in Rural Aleppo

798
00:43:56,958 --> 00:43:59,708
Because I couldn’t bear staying

799
00:43:59,958 --> 00:44:07,416
Even though I stayed away from the
city and avoided any contact with them

800
00:44:08,083 --> 00:44:09,875
Because of my terrible psychological state

801
00:44:10,333 --> 00:44:12,333
Once, I went down to my city

802
00:44:12,416 --> 00:44:14,833
And saw a man killed and crucified

803
00:44:15,541 --> 00:44:19,750
He was wearing an orange jumpsuit and was an elderly man

804
00:44:20,166 --> 00:44:22,000
Not younger than 50 years old

805
00:44:22,416 --> 00:44:24,708
That sight completely destroyed me

806
00:44:24,875 --> 00:44:28,333
And pushed me to leave the area for good

807
00:44:28,500 --> 00:44:30,000
I left by God’s grace

808
00:44:30,208 --> 00:44:31,291
And I didn’t return until after they had left

809
00:44:31,375 --> 00:44:33,958
When the Syrian Democratic Forces took control of the area
